prev":16.15,"latestDate":"2026-07-22","dates":["2021-06-25","2021-07-16","2021-08-06","2021-08-26","2021-09-17","2021-10-07","2021-10-28","2021-11-17","2021-12-09","2021-12-30","2022-01-21","2022-02-10","2022-03-04","2022-03-24","2022-04-14","2022-05-05","2022-05-26","2022-06-15","2022-07-06","2022-07-26","2022-08-16","2022-09-05","2022-09-26","2022-10-14","2022-11-04","2022-11-24","2022-12-15","2023-01-06","2023-01-27","2023-02-16","2023-03-09","2023-03-29","2023-04-20","2023-05-10","2023-05-31","2023-06-20","2023-07-11","2023-07-31","2023-08-21","2023-09-08","2023-09-29","2023-10-19","2023-11-09","2023-11-29","2023-12-20","2024-01-11","2024-02-01","2024-02-21","2024-03-13","2024-04-03","2024-04-24","2024-05-14","2024-06-04","2024-06-24","2024-07-15","2024-08-02","2024-08-23","2024-09-12","2024-10-03","2024-10-23","2024-11-13","2024-12-03","2024-12-24","2025-01-15","2025-02-05","2025-02-25","2025-03-18","2025-04-07","2025-04-29","2025-05-19","2025-06-09","2025-06-27","2025-07-18","2025-08-07","2025-08-28","2025-09-17","2025-10-08","2025-10-28","2025-11-18","2025-12-08","2025-12-30","2026-01-20","2026-02-10","2026-03-02","2026-03-23","2026-04-13","2026-05-04","2026-05-22","2026-06-12","2026-07-02","2026-07-22"],"values":[15.62,18.45,16.15,18.84,20.81,19.54,16.53,17.11,21.58,17.33,28.85,23.91,31.98,21.67,22.7,31.2,27.5,29.62,26.73,24.69,19.69,25.99,32.26,32.02,24.55,20.42,22.83,21.13,18.51,20.17,22.61,19.12,17.17,16.94,17.94,13.88,14.84,13.63,17.13,13.84,17.52,21.4,15.29,12.98,13.67,12.44,13.88,15.34,13.75,14.33,15.97,13.42,13.16,13.33,13.12,23.39,15.86,17.07,20.49,19.24,14.02,13.3,14.27,16.12,15.77,19.43,21.7,46.98,24.17,18.14,17.16,16.32,16.41,16.57,14.43,15.72,16.3,16.42,24.69,16.66,14.33,20.09,17.79,21.44,26.15,19.12,18.29,16.7,17.68,16.15,16.64],"min5y":11.86,"max5y":52.33,"min52":13.47,"max52":31.05}},"commentary":{"source":"claude","generated":"2026-07-24","items":[{"tag":"Energy","text":"<cite index=\"42-4,42-5\">Brent crude prices have risen to around $100 amid Middle East conflict, and inflation volatility is sharply rising again</cite>. WTI and Brent posted +17.5% and +23.4% weekly gains respectively, threatening to reignite core inflation and narrowing the window for Fed easing."},{"tag":"Labor","text":"Claims fell to 187K (down from 217K), and unemployment ticked to 4.2%, but June payrolls were only +57K\u2014a significant deceleration from +129K. <cite index=\"15-7\">Employment in services expanded for the first time in four months at 51.2%</cite>, suggesting stabilization but not robust strength. Labor cooling is structural, not cyclical."},{"tag":"Inflation","text":"CPI headline eased to 3.46% in June but core remains sticky at 2.57%, while <cite index=\"42-1,42-3\">rising inflation volatility is set to trigger earnings disappointments, wider credit spreads and more variability in stock and bond prices</cite>. Energy-driven upside risk now material; Fed policy repricing likely."},{"tag":"Policy/Rates","text":"<cite index=\"2-1\">ECB held deposit rate unchanged at 2.25% at its July decision</cite>, signaling a pause despite energy shocks. UST curve compressed 1bp to 34bp; rates rose 19bp (10Y) on inflation risk and energy shocks. Fed funds locked at 3.75%, but market pricing of future cuts under pressure if energy persists."},{"tag":"Credit Markets","text":"<cite index=\"36-1,36-12,36-13\">Global credit markets demonstrated resilience during H1 2026 due to attractive all-in yields, credit spreads remain tight, and JPM expects spreads to move sideways or widen modestly through H2</cite>. <cite index=\"37-7\">AI is accelerating credit stress in leveraged loans and private credit</cite>. European distress at 5.8% (elevated); CCC underperformance flagged."},{"tag":"Growth","text":"<cite index=\"26-1,26-9\">June retail sales came in at +0.2% m/m (vs +0.3% consensus), but control group advanced 0.5% m/m</cite>, showing underlying resilience despite gasoline deflation. Payroll weakness and slowing housing (starts +19% but existing homes -2.4% YoY) suggest Q3 deceleration risk. GDPNow ticked up to 1.68% but base effects fragile."},{"tag":"Consumer/Housing","text":"Mortgage rates jumped to 6.58% (+9bp) as long-end yields spiked. Housing starts rebounded to 1,427K (+19%) but existing home sales fell 100K to 4.09M, signaling affordability stress and lock-in effect at higher rates. <cite index=\"33-1,33-3\">Apparel retail sales surged 13.65% YoY in June, but seasonal promotions and early back-to-school drove strength</cite>, masking underlying demand softness."}]},"themeCards":[{"title":"Middle East Energy Crisis Reigniting","value":"Acute","dir":"up","statusLine":"Brent crude near $100, WTI +17% weekly on Middle East escalation. Inflation volatility resurgent; price shocks bleeding into core ex-energy.","relevance":"Direct margin compression risk for leveraged borrowers (energy-heavy sectors, hedgers). Credit spreads vulnerable if energy persists; near-term earnings revisions negative for distressed/stress-sensitive credits."},{"title":"Private Credit & Leveraged Loans Under Stress","value":"Elevated","dir":"up","statusLine":"<cite index=\"43-1,43-6\">Private credit faces its most challenging environment since 2008; high-profile leveraged loan defaults in late 2025 and rising use of PIK toggles indicate mounting stress</cite>. European distress ratio at 5.8%.","relevance":"Special situations mandate: <cite index=\"41-1,41-6\">smaller and more leveraged corporates financed by riskier credit markets remain more exposed</cite>. Opportunity in distressed fund dry powder; risk in overlevered borrower refinancing."},{"title":"Payroll Deceleration & Labor Soft-Landing Fragility","value":"Elevated","dir":"down","statusLine":"June payrolls collapsed to +57K (from +129K prior); claims fell but at 187K the labor market is softening structurally. Services employment briefly stabilized but headline momentum weak.","relevance":"Duration risk on credit if labor turns negative sharply. Soft-landing narrative depends on sustained consumer spending; payroll miss suggests consumer income support eroding. Refinancing pressures emerge if defaults accelerate on income stress."},{"title":"Fed Policy Repricing & Duration Reprieve Fading","value":"Emerging","dir":"up","statusLine":"Energy shocks and sticky core (2.57%) are undoing disinflation narrative. Markets repricing fewer Fed cuts; UST 10Y +19bp to 4.67% in days. ECB held, BoE expected to hold; G3 central banks in hold mode amid inflation uncertainty.","relevance":"Negative convexity for HY and leveraged credits; widening likely if repricing accelerates. Floating-rate borrowers benefit short-term but near-term spread volatility high. Refinancing wall (2026-27) at higher terminal rates becomes binding risk."},{"title":"AI-Driven Credit Stress in Select Leveraged Sectors","value":"Live risk","dir":"up","statusLine":"<cite index=\"37-7\">AI is simultaneously supporting record issuance in corporate bonds but accelerating credit stress in leveraged loans and private credit</cite>. Tech-heavy borrowers seeing valuation dislocations.","relevance":"K-shaped bifurcation: AI winners (mega-cap, investment-grade) vs. cyclical/leveraged losers. Special situations: identify stressed borrows with AI-disruption tail risk (retail, logistics, software middle-market). Mispricing opportunities in credits hit by structural AI displacement."},{"title":"Housing Affordability Crunch & Refinancing Lockout","value":"Elevated","dir":"up","statusLine":"Existing home sales declined 2.4% YoY to 4.09M; mortgage rates at 6.58%. Lock-in effect (homeowners at 3-4%) freezing turnover and reducing consumer optionality. Starts up on supply catch-up but demand cracking.","relevance":"Spillover to consumer credit: constrained wealth effect, reduced home-equity borrowing capacity. HELOC/HELOAN refinancing wall at higher rates; mortgage servicer margins compressed. Risk to consumer discretionary credit stress if housing continues deteriorating."}],"extra